<font color="#FF0000">MORE FOR DR. SPATZ............</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb 16 23:45:27 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dr. Spatz:<br><br>
&quot;I think we waste our time and posts on the amnesty issue here.&quot;<br><br>
I disagree.<br>
I feel the amnesty issue is a central one.<br>
I feel the amnesty issue is one of many crucial issues to the feelings many Vietnam Veterans have about themselves.<br><br>
Why would a government (or a society) turn around and forgive someone for breaking a law in the face of those who suffered for not breaking the law, especially in the face of those who perished? Those ultimate unburied dead to whom many of us are inexorably connected in time *are* as invalidated by that act as are those who survived. <br><br>
That's the question.<br>
It is a valid question.<br>
It is worthy of exploration.<br>
Why?<br><br>
Are we dealing with corrupt politics?<br>
Are we dealing with influence peddling by families of the runners?<br>
Are we dealing with a few politicians who tried to symbolically wash the blood from their hands?<br>
Are we dealing with those who tried to bury the whole affair because of guilt?<br>
Why is this such an uncomfortable issue?<br><br>
Regards,<br><br>
Arthur<br><br>
